<p><b>Ronald Dworkin</b>, <a href="/wiki/Queens_Counsel" title="Queens Counsel" class="mw-redirect">QC</a>, <a href="/wiki/British_Academy" title="British Academy">FBA</a> (born December 11, 1931) is an <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">American</a> <a href="/wiki/Legal_philosopher" title="Legal philosopher" class="mw-redirect">legal philosopher</a>, currently professor of <a href="/wiki/Jurisprudence" title="Jurisprudence">Jurisprudence</a> at <a href="/wiki/University_College_London" title="University College London">University College London</a> and the <a href="/wiki/New_York_University_School_of_Law" title="New York University School of Law">New York University School of Law</a>, and former professor of Jurisprudence at the <a href="/wiki/University_of_Oxford" title="University of Oxford">University of Oxford</a>. He is known for his contributions to legal philosophy and <a href="/wiki/Political_philosophy" title="Political philosophy">political philosophy</a>. His theory of <i><a href="/wiki/Law_as_integrity" title="Law as integrity">law as integrity</a></i> is one of the leading contemporary views of the nature of <a href="/wiki/Law" title="Law">law</a>.<sup class="noprint Template-Fact"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources&#160;since March 2009" style="white-space: nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed">citation needed</a></i>]</span></sup></p>
